# PRD: Standardize partial_cmp Error Handling

## 1. Overview

### Problem Statement
Some code uses `.unwrap()` on `partial_cmp()` which panics on NaN values, while other code correctly uses `.unwrap_or(Ordering::Equal)`. This inconsistency creates latent panic risks.

### Objective
Standardize all `partial_cmp()` usage to the safe pattern.

## 2. Current State

### Unsafe Pattern (1 instance found)
```rust
// result_merger.rs:367 - PANICS ON NaN
.max_by(|a, b| a.2.confidence.partial_cmp(&b.2.confidence).unwrap())?;
```

### Safe Pattern (used elsewhere)
```rust
// retry_metrics.rs:754
.unwrap_or(std::cmp::Ordering::Equal)

// generation.rs:556
.sort_by(|a, b| b.1.partial_cmp(&a.1).unwrap_or(std::cmp::Ordering::Equal));

// quantization.rs:125
.max_by(|a, b| a.partial_cmp(b).unwrap_or(std::cmp::Ordering::Equal))
```

## 3. Requirements

| ID | Requirement | Priority |
|----|-------------|----------|
| CMP-001 | All `partial_cmp().unwrap()` SHALL use `unwrap_or` | P0 |
| CMP-002 | Add clippy lint to prevent future regressions | P1 |
| CMP-003 | Document NaN handling policy | P1 |

## 4. Technical Design

### 4.1 Search and Replace
```bash
# Find all instances
rg "partial_cmp.*\.unwrap\(\)" --type rust

# Expected: Only result_merger.rs:367
```

### 4.2 Fix Pattern
```rust
// Before
.max_by(|a, b| a.2.confidence.partial_cmp(&b.2.confidence).unwrap())?;

// After
.max_by(|a, b| {
    a.2.confidence
        .partial_cmp(&b.2.confidence)
        .unwrap_or(std::cmp::Ordering::Equal)
})?;
```

### 4.3 Clippy Configuration
```toml
# clippy.toml or .cargo/config.toml
[lints.clippy]
float_cmp = "warn"
```

### 4.4 Helper Trait (Optional)
```rust
// crates/adapteros-core/src/cmp.rs
pub trait SafePartialOrd {
    fn safe_cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> std::cmp::Ordering;
}

impl SafePartialOrd for f32 {
    fn safe_cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> std::cmp::Ordering {
        self.partial_cmp(other).unwrap_or(std::cmp::Ordering::Equal)
    }
}
```

## 5. Files to Modify

| File | Changes |
|------|---------|
| `agent-spawn/src/result_merger.rs:367` | Fix unsafe unwrap |
| `.cargo/config.toml` | Add clippy lint (optional) |

## 6. Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `rg "partial_cmp.*\.unwrap\(\)" --type rust` returns no results
- [ ] Unit test: NaN confidence values don't panic
- [ ] Clippy passes with float comparison warnings

## 7. Testing

```rust
#[test]
fn test_nan_confidence_handling() {
    let mods = vec![
        (file, line, Proposal { confidence: f32::NAN, .. }),
        (file, line, Proposal { confidence: 0.5, .. }),
    ];

    // Should not panic, should return the non-NaN proposal
    let result = resolve_conflicts(&mods);
    assert!(result.is_some());
}
```

## 8. Scope

This is a small, focused fix:
- 1 file to modify
- 1 line to change
- Prevents panics in production

# PRD: Apply Zeroize Pattern to KMS Credentials

## 1. Overview

### Problem Statement
KMS credentials (`KmsConfig`, `KmsCredentials`) store sensitive keys as plain `String` fields, visible in debug output and not zeroized on drop. The `SecretKey`, `KeyMaterial`, and `SensitiveData` wrappers exist but aren't applied to KMS types.

### Objective
Apply existing zeroize infrastructure to KMS credential types to prevent memory-resident credential exposure.

## 2. Current State

### Existing Zeroize Infrastructure (secret.rs)
```rust
// Already implemented and working
pub struct SecretKey<const N: usize>([u8; N]);  // Zeroize + ZeroizeOnDrop
pub struct KeyMaterial { inner: Vec<u8> }        // Zeroize + ZeroizeOnDrop
pub struct SensitiveData { inner: Vec<u8> }      // Zeroize + ZeroizeOnDrop

// Custom Debug that redacts
impl Debug for SecretKey<N> {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        f.debug_struct("SecretKey").field("redacted", &"[REDACTED]").finish()
    }
}
```

### Gap: KMS Types (providers/kms.rs)
```rust
pub enum KmsCredentials {
    AwsIam {
        access_key_id: String,        // ❌ Plain string
        secret_access_key: String,    // ❌ Visible in debug, not zeroized
        session_token: Option<String>,
        region: String,
    },
    GcpServiceAccount {
        credentials_json: String,     // ❌ Contains private key
    },
    // ...
}
```

### Test Documenting the Gap (kms_security.rs:434)
```rust
// TODO: In production, implement Zeroize trait to prevent credential leaks
let debug_str = format!("{:?}", config);
assert!(!debug_str.is_empty());  // Currently exposes credentials!
```

## 3. Requirements

| ID | Requirement | Priority |
|----|-------------|----------|
| ZER-001 | `secret_access_key` SHALL use `SensitiveData` wrapper | P0 |
| ZER-002 | `credentials_json` SHALL use `SensitiveData` wrapper | P0 |
| ZER-003 | Debug output SHALL show `[REDACTED]` for secrets | P0 |
| ZER-004 | Credentials SHALL zeroize on drop | P0 |
| ZER-005 | Serialization SHALL fail for credential types | P1 |

## 4. Technical Design

### 4.1 Updated KmsCredentials
```rust
use crate::secret::SensitiveData;

#[derive(Clone)]
pub enum KmsCredentials {
    AwsIam {
        access_key_id: String,                    // Not secret (like username)
        secret_access_key: SensitiveData,         // Wrapped
        session_token: Option<SensitiveData>,     // Wrapped
        region: String,
    },
    GcpServiceAccount {
        credentials_json: SensitiveData,          // Wrapped
    },
    AzureKeyVault {
        client_id: String,
        client_secret: SensitiveData,             // Wrapped
        tenant_id: String,
    },
    // ...
}
```

### 4.2 Custom Debug Implementation
```rust
impl Debug for KmsCredentials {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        match self {
            Self::AwsIam { access_key_id, region, .. } => {
                f.debug_struct("AwsIam")
                    .field("access_key_id", access_key_id)
                    .field("secret_access_key", &"[REDACTED]")
                    .field("session_token", &"[REDACTED]")
                    .field("region", region)
                    .finish()
            }
            Self::GcpServiceAccount { .. } => {
                f.debug_struct("GcpServiceAccount")
                    .field("credentials_json", &"[REDACTED]")
                    .finish()
            }
            // ...
        }
    }
}
```

### 4.3 Accessor Methods
```rust
impl KmsCredentials {
    /// Get AWS secret key (for internal use only)
    pub fn aws_secret_key(&self) -> Option<&[u8]> {
        match self {
            Self::AwsIam { secret_access_key, .. } => Some(secret_access_key.as_bytes()),
            _ => None,
        }
    }
}
```

### 4.4 Construction Helpers
```rust
impl KmsCredentials {
    pub fn aws_iam(
        access_key_id: impl Into<String>,
        secret_access_key: impl AsRef<[u8]>,
        region: impl Into<String>,
    ) -> Self {
        Self::AwsIam {
            access_key_id: access_key_id.into(),
            secret_access_key: SensitiveData::new(secret_access_key.as_ref()),
            session_token: None,
            region: region.into(),
        }
    }
}
```

## 5. Files to Modify

| File | Changes |
|------|---------|
| `crypto/src/providers/kms.rs` | Wrap sensitive fields with SensitiveData |
| `crypto/src/providers/kms.rs` | Add custom Debug impl |
| `crypto/tests/kms_security.rs` | Update tests to verify redaction |

## 6. Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `format!("{:?}", kms_config)` shows `[REDACTED]` for secrets
- [ ] Credentials zeroized when `KmsCredentials` drops
- [ ] `serde::Serialize` fails for `SensitiveData` fields
- [ ] Existing KMS functionality unchanged
- [ ] Test verifies debug output contains no actual secrets

## 7. Testing

```rust
#[test]
fn test_credentials_redacted_in_debug() {
    let creds = KmsCredentials::aws_iam(
        "AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE",
        "wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY",
        "us-east-1",
    );

    let debug_str = format!("{:?}", creds);

    // Must not contain actual secret
    assert!(!debug_str.contains("wJalrXUtnFEMI"));
    // Must show redacted
    assert!(debug_str.contains("[REDACTED]"));
}

#[test]
fn test_credentials_zeroize_on_drop() {
    let secret = b"my_secret_key";
    let creds = KmsCredentials::aws_iam("key_id", secret, "us-east-1");

    // Get pointer to internal data before drop
    let ptr = creds.aws_secret_key().unwrap().as_ptr();
    drop(creds);

    // Memory should be zeroed (unsafe check for testing only)
    unsafe {
        let bytes = std::slice::from_raw_parts(ptr, 13);
        assert!(bytes.iter().all(|b| *b == 0));
    }
}
```

# PRD: Complete KV Backend Migration Testing

## 1. Overview

### Problem Statement
The KV backend (redb) is being developed in parallel with SQLite but lacks integration tests for the dual-write migration workflow. Tests are marked `#[ignore]` pending production readiness.

### Objective
Enable and validate the full Phase 4 migration workflow: SqlOnly → DualWrite → KvPrimary.

## 2. Current State

### KV Backend Files (17+ modules)
```
crates/adapteros-db/src/
├── users_kv.rs
├── messages_kv.rs
├── training_datasets_kv.rs
├── repositories_kv.rs
├── collections_kv.rs
├── replay_kv.rs
├── kv_diff.rs
├── kv_isolation_scan.rs
└── ... (9 more)
```

### Ignored Tests (atomic_dual_write_tests.rs:309-325)
```rust
// AUDIT NOTE (2026-01-03): These tests are intentionally #[ignore] because:
// 1. They require a running redb KV backend
// 2. Need `--features kv-backend` flag
// 3. Require temp directory setup

#[tokio::test]
#[ignore = "requires kv-backend feature"]
async fn test_full_migration_workflow() {
    // TODO: Implement when KV backend is production-ready
}
```

### Migration Phases Documented
1. **SqlOnly**: Current production mode
2. **DualWrite (best-effort)**: Write to both, tolerate KV failures
3. **DualWrite (strict)**: Atomic writes to both, rollback on failure
4. **KvPrimary**: Read from KV, write to both, fallback to SQL

## 3. Requirements

| ID | Requirement | Priority |
|----|-------------|----------|
| KV-001 | Enable `kv-backend` feature in CI | P0 |
| KV-002 | Implement test_full_migration_workflow | P0 |
| KV-003 | Test atomic rollback on KV failure | P0 |
| KV-004 | Test SQL fallback when KV unavailable | P1 |
| KV-005 | Benchmark: KV read latency vs SQL | P1 |

## 4. Technical Design

### 4.1 Test Infrastructure
```rust
// tests/kv_migration_tests.rs
use adapteros_db::{Db, StorageMode, KvBackend};
use tempfile::TempDir;

async fn setup_dual_write_test() -> (Db, KvBackend, TempDir) {
    let temp = TempDir::new().unwrap();
    let db = Db::new_in_memory().await.unwrap();
    let kv = KvBackend::new(temp.path().join("test.redb")).await.unwrap();
    db.set_kv_backend(kv.clone());
    (db, kv, temp)
}
```

### 4.2 Migration Workflow Test
```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn test_full_migration_workflow() {
    let (db, kv, _temp) = setup_dual_write_test().await;

    // Phase 1: SQL only
    db.set_storage_mode(StorageMode::SqlOnly);
    let adapter_id = db.register_adapter("test", "hash", "persistent", 8, &[]).await.unwrap();
    assert!(kv.get_adapter(&adapter_id).await.is_err()); // Not in KV

    // Phase 2: Dual-write best-effort
    db.set_storage_mode(StorageMode::DualWriteBestEffort);
    db.update_adapter_rank(&adapter_id, 10).await.unwrap();
    assert_eq!(kv.get_adapter(&adapter_id).await.unwrap().rank, 10); // Now in KV

    // Phase 3: Dual-write strict
    db.set_storage_mode(StorageMode::DualWriteStrict);
    // Simulate KV failure -> should rollback SQL too
    kv.simulate_failure(true);
    let result = db.update_adapter_rank(&adapter_id, 15).await;
    assert!(result.is_err());
    assert_eq!(db.get_adapter(&adapter_id).await.unwrap().rank, 10); // Unchanged
    kv.simulate_failure(false);

    // Phase 4: KV primary
    db.set_storage_mode(StorageMode::KvPrimary);
    let adapter = db.get_adapter(&adapter_id).await.unwrap();
    // Verify read came from KV (check internal metrics)
}
```

### 4.3 CI Configuration
```yaml
# .github/workflows/test.yml
jobs:
  test-kv-backend:
    runs-on: macos-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - name: Run KV backend tests
        run: cargo test -p adapteros-db --features kv-backend -- --ignored
```

## 5. Files to Modify

| File | Changes |
|------|---------|
| `db/tests/atomic_dual_write_tests.rs` | Implement test bodies |
| `db/src/lib.rs` | Add `simulate_failure()` for testing |
| `.github/workflows/test.yml` | Add KV backend job |
| `db/Cargo.toml` | Ensure `kv-backend` feature is defined |

## 6. Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `cargo test -p adapteros-db --features kv-backend -- --ignored` passes
- [ ] Migration workflow test covers all 4 phases
- [ ] Atomic rollback verified on simulated KV failure
- [ ] CI runs KV tests on every PR
- [ ] Performance benchmark: KV read <1ms for adapter lookup

## 7. Risks

- **redb stability**: redb is relatively new; may need fallback plan
- **Data consistency**: Dual-write introduces consistency window
- **Migration rollback**: Need procedure to revert KvPrimary → SqlOnly

# PRD: Sync PolicyId Enum with CLI Range Checks

## 1. Overview

### Problem Statement
The `PolicyId` enum has grown to 29 policies, but CLI validation still checks `1..=25`, preventing access to policies 26-29 (Capability, Language, QueryIntent, LiveData). Documentation says "25 policies" when there are 29.

### Objective
Eliminate hardcoded policy counts by deriving all values from the `PolicyId` enum, ensuring CLI, documentation, and validation stay synchronized.

## 2. Current State Analysis

### PolicyId Enum (registry.rs:12-42)
```rust
pub enum PolicyId {
    Egress = 1,
    Determinism = 2,
    // ... 23 more ...
    CircuitBreaker = 25,
    Capability = 26,      // ❌ Unreachable via CLI ID
    Language = 27,        // ❌ Unreachable via CLI ID
    QueryIntent = 28,     // ❌ Unreachable via CLI ID
    LiveData = 29,        // ❌ Unreachable via CLI ID
}
```

### CLI Validation (policy.rs:204, 287)
```rust
if !(1..=25).contains(&id) {  // ❌ Hardcoded, excludes 26-29
    return Err(AosError::Validation(
        "Policy ID must be between 1 and 25".to_string(),
    ));
}
```

### Display Bug (policy.rs:196)
```rust
println!("\nTotal: {} / 20 policies", filtered.len());  // ❌ Says 20
```

## 3. Requirements

### Functional Requirements
| ID | Requirement | Priority |
|----|-------------|----------|
| POL-001 | CLI SHALL accept all valid PolicyId values (currently 1-29) | P0 |
| POL-002 | Range validation SHALL derive from `PolicyId::all().len()` | P0 |
| POL-003 | Display count SHALL derive from `PolicyId::all().len()` | P0 |
| POL-004 | Add `#[repr(u8)]` and `TryFrom<u8>` to PolicyId | P1 |
| POL-005 | Remove unsafe transmute in favor of safe conversion | P1 |

## 4. Technical Design

### 4.1 Add Repr and TryFrom to PolicyId
```rust
// crates/adapteros-policy/src/registry.rs

#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Hash, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[repr(u8)]  // ADD: Explicit representation
pub enum PolicyId {
    Egress = 1,
    // ...
    LiveData = 29,
}

impl TryFrom<u8> for PolicyId {
    type Error = AosError;

    fn try_from(value: u8) -> Result<Self, Self::Error> {
        // Derive valid range from enum
        let max_id = Self::all().last().map(|p| *p as u8).unwrap_or(0);
        if value < 1 || value > max_id {
            return Err(AosError::Validation(format!(
                "Policy ID must be between 1 and {}", max_id
            )));
        }
        // Safe after validation
        Ok(unsafe { std::mem::transmute(value) })
    }
}

impl PolicyId {
    pub const fn count() -> usize {
        29  // Or use: Self::all().len() in const context
    }

    pub const fn max_id() -> u8 {
        29  // Last variant's discriminant
    }
}
```

### 4.2 Update CLI Validation
```rust
// crates/adapteros-cli/src/commands/policy.rs

fn parse_policy_id(policy_ref: &str) -> Result<PolicyId> {
    if let Ok(id) = policy_ref.parse::<u8>() {
        PolicyId::try_from(id)  // Safe conversion
    } else {
        // Name-based lookup (unchanged)
        list_policies()
            .iter()
            .find(|p| p.name.eq_ignore_ascii_case(policy_ref))
            .map(|p| p.id)
            .ok_or_else(|| AosError::Validation(format!("Policy '{}' not found", policy_ref)))
    }
}
```

### 4.3 Update Display
```rust
println!("\nTotal: {} / {} policies", filtered.len(), PolicyId::count());
```

### 4.4 Update Documentation
```rust
// crates/adapteros-policy/src/registry.rs:1-4
//! Policy Registry - Canonical Policy Packs
//!
//! This module defines the complete set of policy packs enforced by AdapterOS.
//! Currently: 29 policies (IDs 1-29).
```

## 5. Files to Modify

| File | Changes |
|------|---------|
| `policy/src/registry.rs` | Add `#[repr(u8)]`, `TryFrom<u8>`, `count()`, update docs |
| `cli/src/commands/policy.rs` | Use `TryFrom`, derive count from enum |
| `cli/src/commands/policy.rs:196` | Fix "20 policies" display |

## 6. Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `aosctl policy explain 26` works (Capability policy)
- [ ] `aosctl policy explain 29` works (LiveData policy)
- [ ] `aosctl policy list` shows "Total: X / 29 policies"
- [ ] No unsafe transmute without #[repr(u8)] guarantee
- [ ] Adding policy 30 only requires enum change (no hardcoded updates)

## 7. Testing

```bash
# All policy IDs accessible
for i in $(seq 1 29); do
    aosctl policy explain $i || exit 1
done

# Invalid IDs rejected
aosctl policy explain 0 && exit 1   # Should fail
aosctl policy explain 30 && exit 1  # Should fail
aosctl policy explain 999 && exit 1 # Should fail
```

## 8. Future Considerations

- Generate CLI completions from `PolicyId::all()`
- Add `aosctl policy list --ids-only` for scripting
- Consider proc-macro for automatic TryFrom derivation
